Title: La La Land (2016 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì 'Dreamers'
Comment: My intepreation of the film: before Mia and Sebastian met each other, they had their own dreams, which they were chasing. Mia thought her biggest dream was to become an actress and Sebastian thought his biggest dream was to save jazz by opening his own jazz club. but then they met each other and fell in love. It was then where they realized, that the actual dream had always been a quite different one: to find true love. And they did find it in each other. Notice also when "city of stars " was played the first time in the movie, it was right after Sebastian had told mia about his "dream" in the jazz club. But when he sang the line "is this the start of something wonderful, or one more dream, that i cannot make true" .. he was actually singing about the dream to find the true love with mia (he kind of felt, she was the right one just by then), but he was afraid to not being able to make this dream come true, because by that time, Mia was still together with this other Guy Greg. Also when "City of stars" is played in full lenght later, the lyrics lead to this idea as well. In the last scene of La La Land, when they both have the "flashback" of how things should have been going, they both realized, they had given up the real dream: true love. And instead they had followed their other dreams, which is also good, but still the "true dream" had always been a different one...

Lots of people dislike this move because the ending supposedly and apparently ‚Äúsucks‚Äù, but you have to admit, the music and soundtrack to this film is amazing and well-done. Emma Stone and Ryan Gosling‚Äôs phenomenal acting performances really made us think and look deeper into Mia and Sebastian‚Äôs characters, and really put us in their shoes. The movie to me, was as sweet as apple pie, and warm as molten chocolate lava fudge. Especially the ending. 
The ending was not what a lot of people expected, but if they were to look at the lessons that it teaches, isn‚Äôt that the whole point of the ending? The point of life?¬†You encounter something so amazing that you‚Äôd want it for the rest of your life, but you also have to give up another amazing thing to get the new one. You meet someone that instantly lights up your world, and you‚Äôd want and need them in your life, but you can‚Äôt, because your heart tells you that you have to pursue your career that you so longed worked for and respected. You end up facing some difficult choices. Life is like that, and it‚Äôs not always gonna be fair. It‚Äôs not always happy-ever-after. There are paths in life that will force you to make a decision, and sometimes you‚Äôll doubt if you made the right decision. But that‚Äôs life. Not everything will always be your way. The important thing is as long as you listen to your heart.
Cherish the experience you have: show love and respect to all those around you, and make meaningful memories with the ones you love. Maybe sometimes, it‚Äôll work, maybe sometimes it won‚Äôt. Be patient and persevere; when one door closes, another one opens, and you just have to make your own choices in life. And maybe one day, you‚Äôll look back and cherish the memories you have made, the paths you have taken, and the lessons you learned through your experiences. Life isn‚Äôt fair, and it‚Äôs not supposed to be; and not everything is a happy-ever-after. But it‚Äôs all part of the experience, and one day you will look back at these days, at all this pain, and you will cherish it forever. It‚Äôs the decisions that we make today that count and shape our lives, and whether or not we also listened to our heart. Life isn‚Äôt fair, and you won‚Äôt always get the happy ending; but as long as you listen to your heart, and cherish and love those around you, who knows what miracle could drop by your house. Title: La La Land (2016 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì 'Dreamers'
Comment: Well don't get me wrong this is a fine little musical with nice dancing and colors - gotta love that freeway scene...especially if you've ever lived in L.A. I'm thinking this is where all the raves came from about the opening scene, people who actually live in Los Angeles...but then I got to thinking, could I have even sat through this film if I didn't already know and love LA? It's a musical like the Wedding Singer is a musical. Don't get me wrong I loved the Wedding Singer as a teen, but that's about what this amounts to...actually in a way it's worse because it revealed to me that apparently the old white men of the Academy are not only old and white and male, but so brittle and narcissistic that apparently even the struggling actress and underemployed pianist had to be made unrealistically wealthy for this to be a "happy" film...I got a news flash for anyone living in Arkansas: if you come to L.A. to look for an acting or music career, you will be living in a house built in the 1930s divided into four rooms which you will share with 15 people, and you will take public transportation. You will absolutely not be living in a West L.A. art deco apartment or driving a Prius.

Title: La La Land (2016 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì 'Dreamers'
Comment:
Here's a philosophical thought driven by this movie's ending (spoilers ahead) on the nature of storytelling:

Why didn't their relationship work out in the end?

"Because that's the way the film was written," you say.

Why was the film written that way?

"Uh..."

I'll tell you why. Damien Chazelle chose that ending because he didn't want your usual "happily ever after" clich√©. He wanted to do something more original. "Paper Towns" by John Green is another example of this kind of ending. 

But in a story, no part of it (especially the ending/climax) should be chosen for what it is NOT. It should be chosen for what it is. And I see no way this story is made better by that ending, outside of the avoidance of a clich√©.

Comment: Despite the ending, this is a hopelessly optimistic film. It really captures that indomitable spirit of youth that believes that if you want it enough you can make it. The film really is a breath of fresh air that makes you want to believe that life is an adventure and the world is a beautiful place full of hope. Honestly to me the film was really focused on a purity of belief in your passion. That's the thing that bonded the two main leads and its the thing that propelled the entire plot forward. It was incredibly moving and inspiring for anyone who has ever felt like maybe they can't make it or felt that they should just give up on their dreams (so you know everyone). Absolutely beautiful.

Comment:
I give two squats about the Oscars or if this should have gotten an award or not.  I saw this last Friday and decided to check out the trailer for Moonlight. LA LA Land is a fun movie. I'm sure moonlight is probably good and I will likely watch it next. I currently just want something fun. Every movie doesn't have to expose me to some struggle or show me it can be "darker" than the last rendition(Lego Batman even made fun of that trend).

Here is what I took from the movie: If you have a lot of experience with old movies, this one will get your memory going as you'll swear you've seen this scene before.  LA LA land hocks from a lot of old movies. Fred Astair, Danny Kay, Bing Crosby,Debbie Reynolds, Rosemary Clooney, etc. There are a lot of little subtle nods. The main actors even dressed in a similar style. 

Don't see it like it will be nonstop singing(Avita, Les Miserables ,Sweeny Todd), nor like Seven Brides for Seven Brothers.  Maybe a little closer to Singing in the Rain, for song and dance. I wouldn't have minded just a little more dance. Take your wife, take your girlfriend (not at the same time) and just smile.

Was I the only one who didn't like this movie?  Not compared to the hype around it and the money it recieved.  I'd give it a 5 out of 10.  The singers were good, but not great in this quasi-musical.  Compare it to the singing in Les Mis.  There is no comparison.

The move was also slow.  That scene where they were dancing against the purple background was way too long and boring.  

I know why actors in Hollywood would like a movie about this because as actors, they can relate to it.  But I don't know why it made so much money.  Maybe there is a longing out there for musicals so much so that the masses will love any scraps Hollywood with throw them that has 'high production value' and big name actors.

Title: La La Land (2016 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì 'Dreamers'
Comment:
Praise 

A subconscious and unspoken stigma and stereotype exists
among movie producers and most people that a film is for children if it is all
about bright colors, simple messages of happiness and verbally expressed joy
through song and beautiful art as well as principles of familiar real life
things that most good people hold as ideals such as young love or honor in
various jobs. Somehow La La Land proves this utterly wrong and rips those
biases utterly to shreds. It reminds us all that color and life and goodness is
what we are looking to see in real entertainment, which is a childlike feature
in all of us, the innocence we long for. It‚Äôs balance between serious themes
and dreamy heart make it irresistibly attractive and intriguing. It proved that
old fashioned values combined with art in simple and pleasant forms, as applied
to art, are every bit as meaningful and held as respectful to a huge adult
audience by the 340 million it‚Äôs already made. Obviously, it was made after the
way of an older and ‚Äúbygone era‚Äù of films that were classier, more innocent,
more simple, more musical, and more jolly. But I believe it made a masterpiece of
itself accidentally, perhaps because the more youthful producers fill in their
absence of true experience with a bygone genre (the 1920s, 30s, 40s, and 50s)
with their imaginations, that give their forbears the benefit of the doubt in
the way of true quality and meaning, but, who cares? It worked! This film was a
masterpiece among films in my opinion. It proved to me something I have long
believed to the center, which is that part of the glory of being human is to
embrace innocence, and the purer elements of art such as mastery of pictures,
singing, presentations, and dance with honed practice by experienced and
passionate artists‚Ä¶of a kind. La La Land proved to be more than paying homage or
milking nostalgia to some supposedly greater and forgotten era, but a solid and
deliciously indestructible piece of living proof that new and original pieces of
entertainment not only can be made but can make today‚Äôs world brighter and more
beautiful by remaining optimistic, original, and true to form in the process!
This movie is gold! It could hold the potential for some kind of modern renaissance
of worthwhile art in many forms. It didn‚Äôt make me long for the past, it didn‚Äôt
break my heart, but it didn‚Äôt let me away easy either, it didn‚Äôt leave me
critical, it didn‚Äôt leave me without a smile on my face, it didn‚Äôt leave me
content, but it didn‚Äôt leave me unsatisfied, it gave me just that right balance
of entertainment to not only pleasantly distract me away from the woes of real
life but want to get back to it and make something more of it, and that is
meaning! It left me wanting more true art in other forms, and if a movie can
pull at my inner humanity like that, it‚Äôs masterful enough to be called an
original masterpiece, if there ever was one. Like other great movies like Star
Wars, somehow it just hit the spot with the perfect balance of just the right
things; drama, color, comedy, originality, simplicity, easiness of
understanding, heart, a touch of fantasy, a touch of realism, plenty of romance,
seriousness, a little sadness, small aspects of uniqueness, and not overdone in
any of those qualities. For this reason it should stand the test of time. What
a wonderful film. I standards have been raised.

Five out of Five stars.
-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†
Sam Tomlinson¬†¬†¬†¬†
- 2/23/17

Title: La La Land (2016 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì 'Dreamers'
Comment:
Overrated, Over-hyped and trying too much to make an impact. It's a chick flick intended for Ryan Gosling fans and soap opera lovers. The achievement is maybe more on the "Artistic" side, not on the narrative side. The story progresses very slowly, and I kept asking myself - what did the director was trying to say... 
And that is ok, just please don't compare it to classics like star wars or more appropriately - Musicals like "Hair" which is a master piece on its own rights. 14 Oscar nominees ?! hard to believe. I did like the two main actors - they played pretty good, but this movie has to decide what it is... a musical, a romantic film, a get-after-your-dreams movie, an artistic feat  ? I honestly couldn't tell.

Title: La La Land (2016 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì 'Dreamers'
Comment:
I saw the movie today. And I think it was interesting. On one end it paid tribute to the MGM musicals with some of the director shots and that captivating ending (Through the fury camera shots I instantly thought of that 18 minute fantasy break in "American In Paris". But their neat trick is that they used REAL LIFE MOMENTS. Excellent.) I appreciated that aspect of it, as well as the plot, which detailed a unique covenant exchange.

The only negative I have is, while I loved the chemistry between Emma Stone and Ryan Gosling, I wished for more from them in terms of song and dance. If you work with them 3-6 months longer than they might have, you have dance routines akin to Rogers and Astaire. (I felt the choreography was not tight enough) But that's me 1) wanting perfection or 2) actually "holding on to tradition as opposed to moving into the future." - get it?

Overall, the movie was inspiring, as it effortlessly blended a drama-meets-romance plot with musical.  It deserved the many Oscar nominations it received because of its imagery and originality and it was one of the best movies I've seen this year.

Comment: This movie is such a work of art üòç The creativity in this is at maximum from the acting to the notes that would pass through your ears. It gives that feeling of nostalgia, yet it sets a spark of something new. I honestly was watching the movie with a heavy heart solely because of it, and I was shocked to see a 50's style format from such a movie within this period of time! The romanticism of aspirations and dreams caught my attention the best, being both a dreamer and a hopeless romantic. Also, the casting made it even more comfortable for the plot. This is, I think, the third time Emma Stone and Ryan Gosling are paired together in a movie, and that made things easier for me to picture as if everything was merely a memory of some sort. With the colorful sights of LA and the stories of two dreamers clashing into each other, I think this is the best movie for me so far within this year.

Title: La La Land (2016 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì 'Dreamers'
Comment:
La la Land is just amazing. It cured my insomnia and sent me to la la land literally within minutes. But why? 
1. Plot. Nobody watches a musical movie for its plot. But it is unforgivable to conjure up a clear oscar bait with a plot skimpier than Kim K's g-string and as formulaic and unimaginative as Trump's combover. 
2. Music. You can forgive the plot but can you forgive the music since it's a musical movie? None of the tunes is memorable and the score is inferior to even that produced by an amateur funeral band. 
3. The singing. Where do you even begin? We know that both leads are not known for their singing or musical talents but Ryan Gosling's singing can only be described as Kermit warbling in pain when Miss Piggy is not available for the night. At best. 
4. The casting. Gosling clearly looks very uncomfortable throughout the movie and within 20 mins you get a clear sense that he's not even committed or even bothered and he just wishes this nightmare to be over. And Stone? With her resting bitch face (RBF) she would be effective in roles such as the scene-stealing one in Birdman. But as a delusional, campy, act-cute, wide-eyed girl next door with a RBF? Give me a break!! You know something is seriously wrong when John Legend with limited scenes is your best actor. 
5. Lack of chemistry between the co-stars. Let's just say that there's more sexual chemistry if you put Trump and Hillary in the same room. On the same token, it's also more believable for Obama to hump Kim Jong Un than for the leads to get it on. 
6. Dialogue. The script seems to be written by a pre-school kid with mild retardation or a drooling Kanye upon receiving a full mental exorcism la A Clockwork Orange. 
7. Pacing. I snored. The lady to my left snored. The uncle behind me snored. Within 20 minutes. Doesn't help that most scenes are almost akin to that created by a Z grade producer of a third world tourism promotional teaser. 
8. Mandatory conflict scene. It's as intense as a spoilt child having an existential crisis over the fact that he was fed more yellow peas than green peas. 
9. Magical mysticism scene. Ordinarily it would look funny, playful or creative. Here it just looks juvenile, awkward and clumsy. 
10. Ending. Unique and clever and surprising? Nope. Just lazy, manipulative, pretentious and plagiarised hogwash.

It also did not feel like a 2 hour movie, it felt so much faster and kept you entertained the whole time. It is whimsical, depressing, cathartic, old fashioned and inspiring all at once. Lastly, I really liked the ending. It was definitely a more realistic ending. I would definitely see this again and recommend it to everyone!

My broken heart is going to take a long time to heal.

They did this with Brokeback Mountain, Prime, Titanic, Me before You, The Best of Me, Casablanca, Atonement, Becoming Jane, Gone with the Wind, Blue Jay. How many more heartbreaking romance movies have to exist????? In this horrible world we live in (not always horrible, ofc), we already have so much negative stuff happening in the world. Watching a beautiful romance movie with a non-heartbreaking, happy ending where they end up together would allow us all to leave this violent, hateful world temporarily to enjoy this beautiful fictional world. WHY WOULD YOU END IT LIKE THAT??? JUST GIVE US THE CLICHES, idc how annoying and stereotypical it is. I understand this movie was making fun of cliches in Hollywood romance movies how all of them have happy endings, but SO WHAT. Couldn't they have been ironic in making fun of that notion by MAKING it a cliche ending? SO many real life romance stories end well and the couple stays together/stay married for 60 years!! It's not THAT uncommon!

We saw this movie Sunday. It was really good. We make movies for cable. We have our own production equipment. As you know, digital equipment is cheap nowadays. We've made five movies for cable as a family & friends endeavor.  

We are working on a musical script now. We have all the songs. That was easy. Now we have to do stuff like lipsynch the songs and do a LOT of cutaways and montages because we don't want to screw around with sets. We had hoped to make it a Broadway musical. Title: La La Land (2016 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì 'Dreamers'
Comment: Well what a clever and interesting film. The evolution of the musical from Bessie Love and Broadway Melody through to present day and a promising look to the future thankfully avoiding the cliche of "Glee". Paying homage on the way to the masterly Gene Kelly films of the 40's. Twixt all this recognition of its adolescence fruition it tells a modern romantic tale believable and fraught with twists worthy of West Side story and indeed Romeo and Juliet. I can understand the universal acclaim but it seemed to me very much a film makers film and therefore valued by those who value the Art. Not the best film ever but if this is the future of the musical then play on.

I saw it twice at different theaters, both audience reactions was bored by the time the movie ended. My cousin who saw at the second viewing said as a musical it was bland, there wasn't enough musical numbers,the opening number felt out of place, the dancing sucks especially the tap dance sequence a lovely night, singing was mediocre, however she said the songs were good though. Show less

Title: La La Land (2016 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì 'Dreamers'
Comment:
I have said there can be a film with an unoriginal story, but can be made enjoyable with a fresh approach. I don't feel La La Land did that. 

The tunes were unmemerable. If I do think of the score/songs, I'm trying to actually remember them than already humming it. However, City of Stars was quite good. Perhaps a bit over-used, and the first introduction on the pier felt odd and out-of-place. Like, where did it come from suddenly in this film after the previous scene(s)? Same can be said for all other songs, which really are not many at all. 

It's a nice romantic drama film to watch and nice to see both actors together and as their characters. They are quite loveable and cute together. However it was another unoriginal story of struggling actress and musician meet and fall in love and follow dreams together, either ending up successful together or alone. Luckily, their chemistry and warm scenes together make it watchable and not overly distracting.

Maybe the point of the film relates to it's own characters. Trying to be a revolutionist instead of traditionalist. Maybe "La La Land" is trying to be revolutionary and fresh instead of a traditional musical by simply being a romantic drama featuring musical numbers - doing something new than straight-forward and a checklist. But even then, with a part satire and realism of the Los Angeles world, including traffic and constant sun and warmth (that film funnily needed to show time pacing by listing the seasons) it still doesn't come across as anything groundbreaking.

A movie full of SURPISES that combines the prefect proportion of comedy, romance, drama, with some incredibly raw & moving performances. LA LA LAND also displays a very unique film production style, breath-taking sceneries and an over-abundance of amazing talents. Every song transports you to new places, every dance makes you want to dream and every scene leaves you full of WONDER & MAGIC. 
In my opinion, saying that this movie is "Good" would be an understatement, this movie is indeed an outstanding nerve-wrecking and emotional MASTERPIECE. One of the rare movies that brought tears to my eyes and overwhelmed me with an intense and constant overflow of feelings. This movie erased the clear distinction between emotions, leaving you speechless and full of uncertainties.
INSPIRING! I highly recommend this movie as one of the best movie that anyone could watch to perfectly start the new year.

Overall a fantastic movie experience, hope this movie can score Best Picture at the Oscars!!!

Comment: I'm going to be the buzzkill here.  I'm not somebody who falls for hype of any kind when it comes to movies and I think too many are oversold as "best film of the year."  I saw La La Land the other day and was disappointed, quite frankly.  The songs aren't memorable and if you subtract the novelty of these two movie stars singing and dancing you basically have your standard boy-meets-girl movie.  It was inconsistent and I was bored in a couple of places.  And I HATED the ending - I found it depressing.  The upside - Emma Stone's acting was great and Gosling's piano playing was remarkable.  There's much to like about the film but much to dislike as well.

I urge you to see LA LA LAND, if there's one movie to see this Holiday season--THIS IS IT!
If you're a movie buff like me it pays homage to old movies, riffs on Jazz, pursuing and never giving up on your dreams, finding your love and losing them...and the eventual trade-offs as we move on with life and outgrow certain parts of it. Ryan Gosling and Emma Stone definitely more than shines in this glorious movie. Definitely the BEST MOVIE of 2016. It's very French...very "Umbrellas Of Cherbourg".
You'll notice all the "old movie references" in the way it's shot like An American In Paris,  Casabkznca, etc.

Comment:
I've seen "La La Land" and let me tell you...it was original. It was gorgeously fun musical experience I had ever seen. And for all these years that every single musical film tried so hard to have a fun time, but this one it glows me a lot. These two performances were fantastic and they sure have a lot of fun for their life going experience of what they really want for their own dreams. The songs were dazzling and boy, hearing these songs that you can't get out of your head. Yay, take that "Frozen" with "Let It Go" song which people think is cool, but here I can remember them as I can tune my jazzy songs while hearing them in my iPhone. The dance scenes were fun, the real sequences were beautiful and so colorful, and it was an amazing musical film. Like most of the audience since musical films didn't have much potential, but you're watching a fun musical experience. I can't believe this movie it's a huge hit from critically acclaimed people and I'm one of them that no matter what it's a movie classic for the next future. Go check it out people, it was beautiful. One of the best 2016 and I'm not going to say this, but it's easily on my top 10 favorite films that this one deserves it.

[100] üëçüëç ‚≠ê

Title: La La Land (2016 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì 'Dreamers'
Comment:
La la Land is just amazing. It cured my insomnia and sent me to la la land literally within minutes. But why? 
1. Plot. Nobody watches a musical movie for its plot. But it is unforgivable to conjure up a clear oscar bait with a plot skimpier than Kim K's g-string and as formulaic and unimaginative as Trump's combover. 
2. Music. You can forgive the plot but can you forgive the music since it's a musical movie? None of the tunes is memorable and the score is inferior to even that of Nocturnal Animals' (music is not even its key selling point). 
3. The singing. Where do you even begin? We know that both leads are not known for their singing or musical talents but Ryan Gosling's singing can only be described as Kermit warbling in pain when Miss Piggy is not available for the night. At best. 
4. The casting. Gosling clearly looks very uncomfortable throughout the movie and within 20 mins you get a clear sense that he's not even committed or even bothered and he just wishes this nightmare to be over. And Stone? With her resting bitch face (RBF) she would be effective in roles such as the scene-stealing one in Birdman. But as a delusional, campy, act-cute, wide-eyed girl next door with a RBF? Give me a break!! 
5. Lack of chemistry between the co-stars. Let's just say that there's more sexual chemistry if you put Trump and Hillary in the same room. On the same token, it's also more believable for Obama to hump Kim Jong Un than for the leads to get it on. 
6. Dialogue. The script seems to be written by a pre-school kid with mild retardation or a drooling Kanye upon receiving a full mental exorcism la A Clockwork Orange. 
7. Pacing. I snored. The lady to my left snored. The Uncle behind me snored. Within 20 minutes. 
8. Mandatory conflict scene. It's as intense as a spoilt child having an existential crisis over the fact that he was fed more yellow peas than green peas. 
9. Ending. Unique and clever and surprising? Nope. Just lazy and manipulative and pretentious plagiarised hogwash.
